Deep learning techniques can amplify blind spots, and does not engage in critical thinking.   For example, the engine was asked to summarize a blog post.  Summarization has different levels of quality.   Consider what would be expected to summarize 10 pages of code.  Any lead is going to expect one of his developers to quickly summarize what his code is doing.  Now consider a broad domain case to flesh out the complicated issues involved in a good summary.  Consider a cliff notes summary conveying what a political or philosophical work is about.  Firstly, the summarization narrative is tricky because different audiences will summarize what a work is about in very different ways.   It would be a bad summary if they did not relate what the main ideas are from various competing perspectives.  But Chat GPT doesn't really understand the article.   In the case of the blog post on Biden, ChatGPT merely compressed the article but did not perform even a rudimentary summary of what was going on in the article.  For example it does not note that the author consistently cites multiple examples which casts the subject of the article in a particular light consistent with a particular point of view.  This piece was politically conservative, but my point would be identical if the post were more liberal.  The summarization questions are the same.  Were the examples dubious or not?   Was there selective focus- Did the account heavily weight one particular set of examples over another?  How would that weighting be summarized?  Were the stated facts accurate?   For example, in the one used, the author proposed that it was uncommon for foreign dignitaries to utter the phrase God save the Queen when in fact it every foreign dignitary attending a diplomatic dinner in the UK has uttered it as a customary toast.  The article further proposes that gaffes (such as using queen instead of king) are unusual for Biden.   Now, the app could in principle provide guidance to the ChatGPT engine in order to make a structural analysis of the claims made in a body of text in order to better summarize it, but this would be tedious and the better approach is for the quality of the machine learning engine itself to be upgraded in some fundamental ways.    I have seen examples of ChatGPT writing C# code which can't compile because it writes lines that violate its own class declarations.   That's a pretty significant anomaly, so the ability to perform even far more rudimentary sanity checks requires further refinement.

So after digging into the code, I found that Langchain is actually doing the following things: 1. for all your data, store then in vector storage using embeddings; 2. when you query something, it first did a similarity search in the embeddings database, and find out the files that's related to your question; 3. After finding the related files, it takes all the text of that file, together with a context message: "Use the following pieces of context as the 1st system message to answer the user's question. 
If you don't know the answer, just say that you don't know, don't try to make up an answer.
----------------
 {your text data}".  This somehow tells us these points:  1. why it's sometimes not having outside world's information? If the question you asked is not in your document, or if it's not trained on the data for your question, it will return nothing valuable as instructed.   2. Is there a limit on the sizes of your data? Yes, you can't use it with super large files because it's doing a document filtering and it will send all text related to the API server, recently the gpt-3.5-turbo-16k might be the good model to use and it's best the total size of related docs is less than 16k tokens. Which means the best practice would be grouping your data into different topics and try to ensure any query, if responded with similarity search, the total size of returned document is not exceeding the token size limit of the model.  I think16k is roughly the size of a 13-15 pages paper.   3. By removing/changing the system message, you might get better results for common sense questions. I really don't like the system messaged by default, since in a playground, asking gpt-3.5-turbo-16k "Who is George Washington?" will give you better answers comparing to the langchain solution with an empty system message.  4. The langchain is using unstructured library (it reports errors when I didn't install it), which means you can not only use txt files, but also pdf files, word files, etc. Haven't tested it out but highly likely support query of multiple pdf files using similar code in the video. So you can put multiple pdfs in a folder, using a directory index creator and ask questions for your papers, I think (haven't tested it out)  5. The langchain not only supports ChatGPT models, but also other models in the chat_models package. Google PALM2 chat is also supported as of Jul 10, 2023, if someone has the key, you can use other models too. While I don't think PALM2 has the common sense knowledge as good as ChatGPT, but I think it is a better language generating model comparing to at least gpt-3.5-turbo-16k , so PALM2 may produce better results on your data and OpenAI's models are better in answering common sense questions after changing the default system message. The access to new developers will be rolled out until end of July. Another very cool thing is auto-gpt which works great using gpt-4, gpt-3.5 is not smart enough and behaves much worse than gpt-4. If you asked auto-gpt something, it will be able to google itself and replied with the real time information. Also the example of auto-gpt is cool telling you how it could create a recipe based on the next holiday. Hopefully the access to gpt-4 is coming sooner.

Unfortunately not. A problem with the LangChain approach, is that ChatGPT has a limit of 4k-32k tokens (depends on the model) for each conversation. This is about 5k-40k- pages, which is okay for small datasets, but it doesn't work well if you have to cramp huge datasets into the chat message. That's why it doesn't work well with entire codebases, for example.  There are two main technique to deal with the ChatGPT token limitation, both covered on OpenAI's cookbooks.   The first technique is the "fine-tuning". Here you use your own data to train your custom and private model. Using OpenAI's API, you provide a list of inputs and their expected outputs. Once it is finished, you can access the custom model as any other model via their API. The downside: it's expensive and it is not the best if you need to constantly input new data.  The second technique is called "Question answering using embeddings-based search". OpenAI has a tutorial on their GitHub with the same title. This is the technique used on LangChain. Here, you use OpenAI's API to convert a text into an embedding. An embedding is a vector distance: it is an array of floats that represents the semantical distance of something (like a word, a word fragment, a whole sentence, audio, etc), to another something. Here, you can think of an embedding as a hash: you input some content and it returns a sequence of numbers. The returned embedding is always the same for the same input and model. Back to the technique, after converting each document into an embedding, you store them in the local storage for later usage. Then, when you want to ask something to ChatGPT, you convert the question into an embedding (using OpenAI API) and use this value to get the closest documents to the question's embedding ("closest" as in the mathematics' matrices). After all of this, you write your ChatGPT question: you fill the question string with all of your local documents sorted by proximity to the question until the token limit. Then, you prepend your actual question followed by the instructions (ex. "{question} Use the following data to answer the question: {documents}"). You trim the excedent tokens at the end and send to chatgpt.  While this works well for your emails or small snippets of data, it won't work amazingly well for large datasets that have too much dependency on each other. That's why the Twitter example works well for simple questions about the code, but it doesn't perform good for anything that requires to know many parts of codebase at once.

If you want to build an AI tool on the scale of ChatGPT, you would need potentially millions of dollars of investment, if you count R&D too. Even training LLMs on small bits of data is a costly and timely process. I had a project where I had to finetune existing models on .TSV files of language data. I had to do the finetuning on cheaper cloud GPUs. If I had tried to run it on more powerful hardware, it would have cost potentially hundreds just for what is seen as a 'simple' process.  That's not even factoring server costs.  It is really really not as simple as just "Ah I'm gonna use some Python libraries, run the code on text data, then boom I have a new AI tool". It is much more complicated and tiring. That's not even getting into the legal ramifications of training on data.

That's not exactly right.  First of all, finetuning a LLM like ChatGPT isn't the best way to adapt it to your own data. Finetuning is best if you want it to perform a specific task or series of tasks, like if you want to have a pipeline where ChatGPT performs text generation then some specific analysis, etc. Finetuning isn't the best approach if you want to just give ChatGPT extra knowledge through documents (OpenAI say the same thing btw). Finetuning is a costlier approach in terms of price and resources, and doing that just to have ChatGPT know your calendar is overkill.  If you're using embeddings, you're not exactly 'adding' data. You're still sending those vector embeddings along with the prompt.  Right now you can't finetune GPT-4.
